{
  "case_id": "D2N092",
  "method": "medsum_ent",
  "template": "sectioned",
  "summary_text": "Chief Complaint\nPain in the distal radius of the right arm following a tennis injury.\n\nHistory of Present Illness\nThe patient reports pain in the distal radius of his right arm following a tennis injury. He describes hitting a backhand shot, missing the ball, and contacting the net pole with his arm, resulting in immediate pain. He notes some swelling, but not significant. He denies numbness in his hand, but reports some mild pain with wrist movement. He reports a previous fall while doing lawn work, resulting in a stab wound to his arm. He takes flonase for allergies. He has no other surgeries reported.\n\nFindings\nExamination reveals tenderness to palpation over the distal radius of the right arm. Range of motion is limited due to pain. No fracture is palpated. X-ray demonstrates no fractures or significant abnormalities.\n\nAssessment\nThe patient presents with a strained and contused right distal radius, likely secondary to a traumatic injury.\n\nPlan\nWe recommend ice packs to reduce swelling, and 800 milligrams of motrin three times a day with food. Follow up in one week if symptoms do not improve. Schedule physical therapy as appropriate.",
  "reference_summary": "CC:\n\nRight arm pain.\n\nHPI:\n\nMs. Martinez is a 43-year-old female who presents today for an evaluation of right arm pain after she hitting her arm on a pole while playing tennis. She had mild swelling at the time. There is pain with motion. She denies any numbness or tingling in her hand. She has a past medical history of allergies and takes Flonase.\n\nEXAM\n\nExamination of the left wrist shows tenderness over the distal radius and pain with flexion of the wrist and thumb.\n\nRESULTS\n\nX-rays of the left wrist show no obvious signs of acute fracture or other abnormality.\n\nIMPRESSION\n\nRight wrist sprain.\n\nPLAN\n\nAt this point, I discussed the diagnosis and treatment options with the patient. I have recommended ice and anti-inflammatory medications. I am prescribing Motrin, 800 mg to take 3 times a day with food. She will follow up with me in 1 week or as needed.",
